00:12:22.550 --> 00:12:25.750
and most importantly the computer

00:12:25.750 --> 00:12:29.640
on which I had stored everything I
had written in my graduate program.

00:12:29.640 --> 00:12:32.010
Like three years of
writing, a book in progress,

00:12:32.010 --> 00:12:35.330
all of it was just
gone all of a sudden.

00:12:35.330 --> 00:12:37.680
And you ask me, "Did
you back it up?"

00:12:37.680 --> 00:12:38.980
And I would say, "Yes.

00:12:38.980 --> 00:12:43.660
I back it up on CDs that were
stored stupidly right next

00:12:43.660 --> 00:12:44.960
to the computer."

00:12:44.960 --> 00:12:46.260
So they were stolen too.

00:12:46.260 --> 00:12:50.850
As a side note to this story, I
then sent out hundreds of fliers

00:12:50.850 --> 00:12:54.150
to the area pawn shops saying like,
"If you see this computer, call me.

00:12:54.150 --> 00:12:56.540
I will buy it, no questions asked."

00:12:56.540 --> 00:13:00.750 position:56%
And like a day later I got a phone
call from a guy who ran a pawn shop.

00:13:00.750 --> 00:13:02.650
He's like, "Are you the
guy with the computer?"

00:13:02.650 --> 00:13:03.950
I said, "Yes."

00:13:03.950 --> 00:13:05.250
My heart was singing, "Yes.

00:13:05.250 --> 00:13:06.550
I'm the guy with the computer."

00:13:06.550 --> 00:13:07.850
He says, "Yeah.

00:13:07.850 --> 00:13:09.150
You're never going
to see that again."

00:13:09.150 --> 00:13:10.860
I was like, "Why?"

00:13:10.860 --> 00:13:12.160
He's like, "It's too old.

00:13:12.160 --> 00:13:13.460
Nobody would buy it.

00:13:13.460 --> 00:13:14.760
Check the dumpsters."

00:13:14.760 --> 00:13:16.060
I'm like, "Oh, god."

00:13:16.060 --> 00:13:17.860
You know? So it was like just
twisting it a little bit.

00:13:17.860 --> 00:13:20.040
And so I had no writing.

00:13:20.040 --> 00:13:21.390
I had nothing.

00:13:21.390 --> 00:13:23.040
So I had to start over.

00:13:23.040 --> 00:13:24.580
And so I kind of couldn't bear it.

00:13:24.580 --> 00:13:27.110
It was just too heartbreaking to
like continue working on the thing

00:13:27.110 --> 00:13:28.410
that I'd already been working on.

00:13:28.410 --> 00:13:30.450
It was just too filled with
negative emotion for me

00:13:30.450 --> 00:13:32.010
to like be -- to work on it.

00:13:32.010 --> 00:13:34.640
So I was like, "I'm just
going to start something new."

00:13:34.640 --> 00:13:37.780
And so I decided to write about
the thing that was most interesting

00:13:37.780 --> 00:13:39.820
that I'd seen recently
which was the protest

00:13:39.820 --> 00:13:42.150
at the republican nominating
convention.

00:13:42.150 --> 00:13:44.620
And I didn't know it at
the time, but that ended

00:13:44.620 --> 00:13:46.470
up being the first words
I wrote for "The Nix."

00:13:46.470 --> 00:13:49.420
It was about these protests.

00:13:49.420 --> 00:13:50.720
And one of the things
that one of the --

00:13:50.720 --> 00:13:53.710
Like the talking head cable news
type folks were saying at the time,

00:13:53.710 --> 00:13:58.300
they were asking if the protests in
2004 were going to get as violent

00:13:58.300 --> 00:14:01.540
as the protests in Chicago in 1968.

00:14:01.540 --> 00:14:03.130
And I was really dumb.

00:14:03.130 --> 00:14:05.740
I was like, "What happened
in Chicago in 1968?"

00:14:05.740 --> 00:14:07.040
I had no idea.

00:14:07.040 --> 00:14:08.340
I'd lived in Chicago.

00:14:08.340 --> 00:14:10.410
I spent lots of time there.

00:14:10.410 --> 00:14:11.710
I had no idea what had happened.

00:14:11.710 --> 00:14:13.010
I was very naive.

00:14:13.010 --> 00:14:16.190
So I looked it up, and I saw that
there was this amazing history

00:14:16.190 --> 00:14:18.080
that I was completely unaware of.

00:14:18.080 --> 00:14:22.170
And the more I looked in to it,
comparing these two protests,

00:14:22.170 --> 00:14:27.750
'68 and 2004, the more it just
something about it hooked me.

00:14:27.750 --> 00:14:29.960
I realized that I was
looking at something

00:14:29.960 --> 00:14:31.370
that felt sort of familiar.

00:14:31.370 --> 00:14:36.460
One journalist in 1968 in Chicago
described it as the tectonic plates

00:14:36.460 --> 00:14:38.750
in American political life grinding

00:14:38.750 --> 00:14:40.930
against each other
on Michigan Avenue.

00:14:40.930 --> 00:14:44.090
And in some ways that felt like
-- That felt very familiar.

00:14:44.090 --> 00:14:48.170
Even in 2004, it felt like the
world was getting much more --

00:14:48.170 --> 00:14:51.480
The political life of the country
was getting much more polarized.

00:14:51.480 --> 00:14:54.130
I noticed that conversations
between people in different ends

00:14:54.130 --> 00:14:55.900
of the political spectrum
were getting more strained

00:14:55.900 --> 00:14:57.200
and more strained.

00:14:57.200 --> 00:14:58.580
And so it felt relevant.

00:14:58.580 --> 00:15:01.780
I didn't know quite what
I wanted to say about it.

00:15:01.780 --> 00:15:04.810
I didn't know quite how
it would turn into a plot,

00:15:04.810 --> 00:15:08.450
but it felt like it burned
for me for some reason.

00:15:08.450 --> 00:15:10.820
And there -- Two studies
came out recently.

00:15:10.820 --> 00:15:12.770
I didn't know this at the
time, but two studies came

00:15:12.770 --> 00:15:15.510
out recently about
this very subject.

00:15:15.510 --> 00:15:18.670
And in one there's a
survey done in 1960

00:15:18.670 --> 00:15:21.850
that asked American adults
whether it would disturb them

00:15:21.850 --> 00:15:26.060
if their child married a member
of the other political party,

00:15:26.060 --> 00:15:28.350
if it would disturb them.

00:15:28.350 --> 00:15:32.490
And in 1960 no more than 5%
said yes in either party.

00:15:32.490 --> 00:15:35.290
In 2010 they asked that question.

00:15:35.290 --> 00:15:39.680
That question was asked again, and
this time 33% of democrats and 40%

00:15:39.680 --> 00:15:42.440
of republicans said yes,
it would disturb them

00:15:42.440 --> 00:15:45.130
if their child married someone
from the other political party.

00:15:45.130 --> 00:15:47.900
And that was a bigger
number than nationality,

00:15:47.900 --> 00:15:51.230
than religion, than race.

00:15:51.230 --> 00:15:56.510
That partyism ended up being kind
of the line that people drew.

00:15:56.510 --> 00:16:01.710
And a more recent study showed
that they've been doing a survey

00:16:01.710 --> 00:16:04.810
of college freshmen every
year for many, many years,

00:16:04.810 --> 00:16:06.580
and one of the questions
they asked is about,

00:16:06.580 --> 00:16:08.600
you know, their political views.

00:16:08.600 --> 00:16:12.700
And this year's incoming
freshman class is --

00:16:12.700 --> 00:16:15.790
shows the fewest number
of political moderates

00:16:15.790 --> 00:16:19.170
that we've seen since 1968.

00:16:19.170 --> 00:16:21.600
So every time I would kind
of look in to this more,

00:16:21.600 --> 00:16:25.120
it just felt like there
were certain symmetries

00:16:25.120 --> 00:16:27.140
between the political
moment I was living

00:16:27.140 --> 00:16:30.230
through from 2004 to
the present and 1968.

00:16:30.230 --> 00:16:31.530
It just felt important to me.

00:16:31.530 --> 00:16:32.830
So I put it in to the book.

00:16:32.830 --> 00:16:34.570
I didn't know quite what
was going to happen with it,

00:16:34.570 --> 00:16:36.170
but I put it in to the book.

00:16:36.170 --> 00:16:40.120
The other thing on a separate like
parallel track from all of this,

00:16:40.120 --> 00:16:42.470
I started playing video games.

00:16:42.470 --> 00:16:46.860
You would think that those
wouldn't relate at all,

00:16:46.860 --> 00:16:51.580 position:56%
but after all of my stuff was stolen
in New York and I was quite sad,

00:16:51.580 --> 00:16:55.070
and things weren't quite
going very well at the time,

00:16:55.070 --> 00:16:57.450
I was doing very little writing.

00:16:57.450 --> 00:16:59.770
I was sort of broke.

00:16:59.770 --> 00:17:03.660
I was working at a
nonprofit poetry organization.

00:17:03.660 --> 00:17:06.550
So you can imagine what
my salary was, you know.

00:17:06.550 --> 00:17:10.360
And so a friend of
mine, he called me.

00:17:10.360 --> 00:17:12.550
He says, "I want you
to buy this video game.

00:17:12.550 --> 00:17:13.850
We're going to play it together."

00:17:13.850 --> 00:17:15.150
And I said, "What's the game?"

00:17:15.150 --> 00:17:18.180
He said, "It's called
'World of Warcraft.'"

00:17:18.180 --> 00:17:19.480
And I was like, "What's that?"

00:17:19.480 --> 00:17:20.780
I'd never heard of it.

00:17:20.780 --> 00:17:22.080
He's like, "Just trust me.

00:17:22.080 --> 00:17:23.380
Just buy it."

00:17:23.380 --> 00:17:24.680
So I'm like, "Okay."

00:17:24.680 --> 00:17:25.980
So I bought it.

00:17:25.980 --> 00:17:27.280
And we played, and he has since
told me that the only reason he did

00:17:27.280 --> 00:17:28.580 position:56%
that was because you can chat with
the other person that you're playing

00:17:28.580 --> 00:17:29.880 position:56%
with other -- You know, on the game.

00:17:29.880 --> 00:17:31.180
And so he just wanted
to keep an eye on me.

00:17:31.180 --> 00:17:32.480
He's a very good friend.

00:17:32.480 --> 00:17:33.780
He's very sweet.

00:17:33.780 --> 00:17:35.080
He just wanted to make
sure I was okay.

00:17:35.080 --> 00:17:37.040
So we played the game every
night, and we would talk.

00:17:37.040 --> 00:17:38.760
And this went on for about six

00:17:38.760 --> 00:17:40.350
to eight months before he
finally got sick of it.

00:17:40.350 --> 00:17:41.650
He's like, "No.

00:17:41.650 --> 00:17:42.950
I can't play this anymore."

00:17:42.950 --> 00:17:44.680
And so he quit, but
I just kept going.

00:17:44.680 --> 00:17:48.340
Like I had never really been
a gamer before in my life.

00:17:48.340 --> 00:17:51.640
Like I donated one summer when
I was maybe in fourth grade

00:17:51.640 --> 00:17:52.940
to beating "The Legend of Zelda."

00:17:52.940 --> 00:17:54.870
And other than that I've
never really played.

00:17:54.870 --> 00:17:58.700
But I played just the crap
out of "World of Warcraft."

00:17:58.700 --> 00:18:02.800 position:56%
And if you don't know anything about
it, it's really embarrassing for me

00:18:02.800 --> 00:18:05.800
to talk about it now, but if you
don't know anything about it,

00:18:05.800 --> 00:18:10.480
it's like imagine like "Lord of
the Rings," you know, like elves

00:18:10.480 --> 00:18:12.540
and dragons and that kind of
stuff, but with like millions

00:18:12.540 --> 00:18:15.000
of people playing simultaneously.

00:18:15.000 --> 00:18:17.270
And I played it so much that
even after I left New York

00:18:17.270 --> 00:18:20.070 position:56%
after a couple years I kept playing,

00:18:20.070 --> 00:18:23.490
and I would like cancel social
engagements because I had

00:18:23.490 --> 00:18:26.470
to go raid with my guild, you know.

00:18:26.470 --> 00:18:30.850
And I got really good at
it, really good at it.

00:18:30.850 --> 00:18:33.020
And it's a complicated game,
and when you get really good

00:18:33.020 --> 00:18:35.840
at it you feel good about that.

00:18:35.840 --> 00:18:39.590
And I don't think I would
describe it at the time this way,

00:18:39.590 --> 00:18:44.510
but now I do which is that it was
in some ways emotionally analgesic.

00:18:44.510 --> 00:18:46.940
It was kind of it was
my painkiller, you know.

00:18:46.940 --> 00:18:50.320 position:56%
Like nothing else was going very
well, but at least I could come home

00:18:50.320 --> 00:18:53.180
at the end of the day and fire
up this thing and get on board

00:18:53.180 --> 00:18:55.620
with a bunch of other people
who we all respected each other

00:18:55.620 --> 00:18:56.920
for being good at this thing.

00:18:56.920 --> 00:18:58.710
And it was really important
to be good at this thing

00:18:58.710 --> 00:19:00.630
when everything else
was going poorly.

00:19:00.630 --> 00:19:03.310
And it was also an effective
distraction from kind

00:19:03.310 --> 00:19:04.610
of the real world for
a little while.

00:19:04.610 --> 00:19:06.410
But then fast forward
three or four years

00:19:06.410 --> 00:19:09.930
and I realized I absolutely
could not be distracted

00:19:09.930 --> 00:19:12.050
from the real world anymore,
spending way too much time

00:19:12.050 --> 00:19:15.100
in this digital world, and so I
had to abandon it and I quit kind

00:19:15.100 --> 00:19:17.020
of cold turkey and
haven't played since.

00:19:17.020 --> 00:19:19.860
But there's something
about it, about that kind

00:19:19.860 --> 00:19:23.160
of love/hate relationship
I had with the game.

00:19:23.160 --> 00:19:26.960
I appreciated how it helped me get
through a dark time in my life,

00:19:26.960 --> 00:19:31.550
but at the same time I really like
resented that it took so much time.

00:19:31.550 --> 00:19:34.130
And also I had to like admit to
my friends I was doing something

00:19:34.130 --> 00:19:35.680
that 12 year olds also do.

00:19:35.680 --> 00:19:37.680
You know? So -- And so this kind

00:19:37.680 --> 00:19:40.590
of love/hate ambivalent thing,
I felt like it was good.

00:19:40.590 --> 00:19:42.590
It was good fodder
to treat in fiction.

00:19:42.590 --> 00:19:45.990
I'd never seen fiction do
this to a video game before.

00:19:45.990 --> 00:19:47.500
So I'm like, "Well, why not try?"

00:19:47.500 --> 00:19:49.320
So I threw it in to the book.

00:19:49.320 --> 00:19:51.590
I didn't know how it
would be relevant,

00:19:51.590 --> 00:19:53.440
but I put it in to the
book and I was like, "Well,

00:19:53.440 --> 00:19:56.390
let's see if I can
connect this in some way."

00:19:56.390 --> 00:19:59.560
At the same time, I leave New York.

00:19:59.560 --> 00:20:00.860
I move to Florida.

00:20:00.860 --> 00:20:04.080
I live in Naples, Florida which is
this cozy little beach community

00:20:04.080 --> 00:20:05.380
on the Gulf of Mexico.

00:20:05.380 --> 00:20:06.680
And I went there to teach.

00:20:06.680 --> 00:20:09.350
I got a job teaching at
Florida Gulf Coast University.

00:20:09.350 --> 00:20:12.240
And so for a long time -- I
did this for about 10 years.

00:20:12.240 --> 00:20:16.220
For a long time I thought of myself
more as a teacher than a writer.

00:20:16.220 --> 00:20:19.870
And I would -- You know, I kind
of threw myself in to teaching,

00:20:19.870 --> 00:20:22.980
and I kept on having these
experiences with students

00:20:22.980 --> 00:20:24.920
that were really shocking to me.

00:20:24.920 --> 00:20:29.020
A good -- I'll tell
you two quick stories.

00:20:29.020 --> 00:20:32.510
The first one was my
first semester teaching,

00:20:32.510 --> 00:20:35.670
and I taught first year writing
classes, composition one.

00:20:35.670 --> 00:20:38.790
And I go in to my first class
to teach and there's 25 students

00:20:38.790 --> 00:20:41.440
in the room, and I teach
my class and I go home.

00:20:41.440 --> 00:20:44.000
And I come back like two days
later for the second class

00:20:44.000 --> 00:20:47.880
and of the 25 students,
21 still remain.

00:20:47.880 --> 00:20:49.180
And this happens.

00:20:49.180 --> 00:20:50.910
Like they shop around and
like take, you know --

00:20:50.910 --> 00:20:52.930
drop and add and so forth.

00:20:52.930 --> 00:20:56.560
And so of the four people
who dropped the class,

00:20:56.560 --> 00:20:59.130
three of them eventually
their names fell off

00:20:59.130 --> 00:21:01.890
of my online roll,
but one name stayed.

00:21:01.890 --> 00:21:04.150
And I kept on waiting
for this name to leave.

00:21:04.150 --> 00:21:07.410
I kept on waiting for her to drop
the class, and she just never did.

00:21:07.410 --> 00:21:09.480
Eventually I just kind
of forgot about it.

00:21:09.480 --> 00:21:11.550
And I taught my class, and
it's the end of the semester.

00:21:11.550 --> 00:21:14.530
It's the last class
before finals week.

00:21:14.530 --> 00:21:18.450
And I walk in to teach and
there's this new person

00:21:18.450 --> 00:21:19.750
in the back of the room.

00:21:19.750 --> 00:21:21.050
I was like, "Hi.

00:21:21.050 --> 00:21:22.350
Who are you?"

00:21:22.350 --> 00:21:23.650
And she says this name.

00:21:23.650 --> 00:21:25.150
It's the name from the roll.

00:21:25.150 --> 00:21:30.540
And she hasn't been there since day
one, and I'm like, "Welcome back."

00:21:30.540 --> 00:21:34.520
You know? And I teach my class
and she comes up to me at the end

00:21:34.520 --> 00:21:39.460
of class and she says, and this
is a quote, I swear to God.

00:21:39.460 --> 00:21:43.270
She says, "So I think I've fallen
a little behind in your class.

00:21:43.270 --> 00:21:51.230
What extra credit can I
do to get a good grade?"

00:21:51.230 --> 00:21:55.030
Not to pass, but to
like get a good grade.

00:21:55.030 --> 00:21:58.050
I was like, "There's
not enough extra credit.

00:21:58.050 --> 00:22:00.300
Like you've missed
literally the entire semester.

00:22:00.300 --> 00:22:03.650
Like you've missed every
single assignment."

00:22:03.650 --> 00:22:05.050
And she's like, "Seriously?"

00:22:05.050 --> 00:22:06.350 position:56%
And she was really upset about this.

00:22:06.350 --> 00:22:07.650
She's like, "You're
going to fail me?"

00:22:07.650 --> 00:22:09.750
And I'm like, "Well, it's
not -- It wasn't my choice.

00:22:09.750 --> 00:22:11.500
Like you just didn't
do any of the work."

00:22:11.500 --> 00:22:16.200
And she's like, you know -- I
told her that the school had this

00:22:16.200 --> 00:22:18.100
like really generous thing, policy,

00:22:18.100 --> 00:22:20.510
like she just retakes
the class next semester

00:22:20.510 --> 00:22:23.280
and whatever grade she
gets will replace the F.

00:22:23.280 --> 00:22:26.720
And so it will not even be
on her transcript or her GPA.

00:22:26.720 --> 00:22:28.020
No problem.

00:22:28.020 --> 00:22:29.320
She's like she wasn't
satisfied with that,

00:22:29.320 --> 00:22:30.790
and kind of leaves really angry.

00:22:30.790 --> 00:22:36.580
And then like on a hunch like two
days later I check this website,

00:22:36.580 --> 00:22:38.310
ratemyprofessors.com.

00:22:38.310 --> 00:22:40.860
I don't know if you
know this website.

00:22:40.860 --> 00:22:42.510
It's like Yelp for teachers.

00:22:42.510 --> 00:22:44.080
It's terrible.

00:22:44.080 --> 00:22:47.710
And sure enough there was a brand
new review of me posted anonymously

00:22:47.710 --> 00:22:51.040
that said, "I asked this guy for
help and he refused to help me.

00:22:51.040 --> 00:22:52.340
He's a jackass."

00:22:52.340 --> 00:22:53.640
Like, oh, okay.

00:22:53.640 --> 00:22:54.940
Welcome to teaching.

00:22:54.940 --> 00:22:58.630
And the other story that kind
