00:23:17.100 --> 00:23:19.400
It's weird."

00:23:20.510 --> 00:23:27.250
[ Laughter ]

00:23:27.250 --> 00:23:29.660
I said, "What do you mean weird?"

00:23:29.660 --> 00:23:31.300
She's like, "I don't know.

00:23:31.300 --> 00:23:32.900
It's just weird."

00:23:32.900 --> 00:23:34.820
I'm like, "Is it like
-- Is it a coincidence?

00:23:34.820 --> 00:23:38.410
Like did you accidentally type
exactly what was on this website?"

00:23:38.410 --> 00:23:39.710
She's like, "I don't know.

00:23:39.710 --> 00:23:46.410
It's just weird, and
my dad's a lawyer."

00:23:46.410 --> 00:23:47.710
Right. So yeah.

00:23:47.710 --> 00:23:50.770
I -- And so I kept on having
these kinds of experiences.

00:23:50.770 --> 00:23:52.150
I kept on -- And just
I couldn't figure

00:23:52.150 --> 00:23:54.310
out like what is going
on with my students.

00:23:54.310 --> 00:23:57.160
And I should say like most college
students are, you know, wonderful,

00:23:57.160 --> 00:24:00.730 position:56%
hard working people, but I had
enough of these types of experiences

00:24:00.730 --> 00:24:03.330 position:56%
and my colleagues in the
profession had enough of these types

00:24:03.330 --> 00:24:05.380
of experiences that
it felt like a trend.

00:24:05.380 --> 00:24:08.040
It felt like something
weird was going on.

00:24:08.040 --> 00:24:11.460
And I couldn't quite figure it out.

00:24:11.460 --> 00:24:14.670
And so I started writing about
it because again I tend to like

00:24:14.670 --> 00:24:17.030
to write about something
that I'm confused about.

00:24:17.030 --> 00:24:21.720
And so this character appeared in
the novel one day, Laura Pottsdam,

00:24:21.720 --> 00:24:24.570
if you've read the book, and
she became the embodiment

00:24:24.570 --> 00:24:25.870
of all of these students.

00:24:25.870 --> 00:24:28.500
And then like you do -- Almost
like you do in real life,

00:24:28.500 --> 00:24:29.830
you know, you meet someone.

00:24:29.830 --> 00:24:31.130 position:56%
You have a first impression of them.

00:24:31.130 --> 00:24:33.320
And then you interrogate that
first impression over and over

00:24:33.320 --> 00:24:35.000
and over again as you
get to know them.

00:24:35.000 --> 00:24:38.710 position:56%
And as I got to know Laura, as I got
to know my own real life students,

00:24:38.710 --> 00:24:42.210
I began to realize what was maybe
going on which is that they --

00:24:42.210 --> 00:24:45.460
They came to college in
a different environment

00:24:45.460 --> 00:24:46.760
than I came to college in.

00:24:46.760 --> 00:24:48.890
You know, they grew
up during a recession.

00:24:48.890 --> 00:24:51.970
They grew up during
tight times, you know.

00:24:51.970 --> 00:24:54.670
And they had been given
advice by, you know,

00:24:54.670 --> 00:24:58.500
people that were well
meaning and loved them,

00:24:58.500 --> 00:25:02.350 position:56%
but maybe bad advice about, you
know, the purpose of college is just

00:25:02.350 --> 00:25:03.650
to secure yourself a job.

00:25:03.650 --> 00:25:06.960
It's a tight, you know,
brutal economy.

00:25:06.960 --> 00:25:10.740
And so you don't have time for
things like writing and poetry.

00:25:10.740 --> 00:25:13.750 position:56%
Like go out and get something that's
just job training for something

00:25:13.750 --> 00:25:16.330
that will pay you well
because it's a global economy

00:25:16.330 --> 00:25:18.320
