isolating and lonely that can feel.

00:28:29.100 --> 00:28:31.520
So that's what I gave to
Samuel, the abandoned kid.

00:28:31.520 --> 00:28:34.620
Like this kind of sense of
isolation and loneliness, you know,

00:28:34.620 --> 00:28:36.800
that I felt in those moments.

00:28:36.800 --> 00:28:39.560
So then, you know, so you
have all these things in play.

00:28:39.560 --> 00:28:41.230
And you're like, "Well,
how do they all connect?"

00:28:41.230 --> 00:28:44.470
And I realized maybe six or
seven years in to the process --

00:28:44.470 --> 00:28:48.280
I realized that they all
connected because they're all ways

00:28:48.280 --> 00:28:51.570
where first people have sort
of walled themselves off

00:28:51.570 --> 00:28:53.670
in their own world, and second,

00:28:53.670 --> 00:28:56.280
ways in which people have lost
the ability to communicate

00:28:56.280 --> 00:28:58.730
with people outside of that world.

00:28:58.730 --> 00:29:00.790
So it's -- I think this is
true for people who are --

00:29:00.790 --> 00:29:04.090
certain people who are totally
committed to political ideologies,

00:29:04.090 --> 00:29:08.840
to gamers, to people obsessed
with their social image status,

00:29:08.840 --> 00:29:12.160
to people obsessed with
their devices or even people

00:29:12.160 --> 00:29:16.330
in relationships who for one
reason or another grow apart,

00:29:16.330 --> 00:29:19.790
stop communicating, and suddenly
seem like strangers to each other.

00:29:19.790 --> 00:29:22.830
So I realized that this was a
novel actually about isolation,

00:29:22.830 --> 00:29:25.360
about disconnection,
about living in a bubble

00:29:25.360 --> 00:29:27.220
of your own mind's creation.

00:29:27.220 --> 00:29:29.340
So I realized this wasn't
actually a protest novel,

00:29:29.340 --> 00:29:32.460
but rather the protest stuff
was just a kind of backdrop

00:29:32.460 --> 00:29:34.820
for what was actually
happening with my characters.

00:29:34.820 --> 00:29:38.190
That it was more like a
baseline instead of the melody.

00:29:38.190 --> 00:29:41.720
And that's why revision is
so important because then

00:29:41.720 --> 00:29:45.320
after nine years of doing this I
got to go back and make it seem

00:29:45.320 --> 00:29:47.810
like I intended to
do that all along.

00:29:47.810 --> 00:29:51.480
And so the neat thing that
happens is about -- This --

00:29:51.480 --> 00:29:54.340
You know, this far in to the
process suddenly you begin

00:29:54.340 --> 00:29:55.640
to understand what you're doing.

00:29:55.640 --> 00:30:00.560
And you get to be intentional where
before you were maybe instinctive.

00:30:00.560 --> 00:30:04.530
So if this is a novel about our
inability to see each other,

00:30:04.530 --> 00:30:05.930
listen to each other,
how do I capture

00:30:05.930 --> 00:30:07.980
that on a smaller scale,
on a human scale?

00:30:07.980 --> 00:30:11.080
It would be pretty boring if I
just wrote about kind of democrats

00:30:11.080 --> 00:30:12.380
and republicans fighting.

00:30:12.380 --> 00:30:14.040
How can I make that personal?

00:30:14.040 --> 00:30:17.550
So I wanted just to read you
the prologue from the novel.

00:30:17.550 --> 00:30:21.110
With these ideas in mind about
how people can kind of grow

00:30:21.110 --> 00:30:24.370
to live inside their own heads,
their own private worlds,

00:30:24.370 --> 00:30:28.320
and how even people who live
together can be total mysteries

00:30:28.320 --> 00:30:31.850
to each other.

00:30:31.850 --> 00:30:33.820
"If Samuel had known
his mother was leaving,

00:30:33.820 --> 00:30:35.700
he might have paid more attention.

00:30:35.700 --> 00:30:37.890
He might have listened
more carefully to her,

00:30:37.890 --> 00:30:42.170
observed her more closely, written
certain crucial things down.

00:30:42.170 --> 00:30:43.920
Maybe he could have
acted differently,

00:30:43.920 --> 00:30:47.010
spoken differently,
been a different person.

00:30:47.010 --> 00:30:50.660
Maybe he could have been a
child worth sticking around for.

00:30:50.660 --> 00:30:53.000
But Samuel did not know
his mother was leaving.

00:30:53.000 --> 00:30:56.210
He did not know she had been
leaving for many months now,

00:30:56.210 --> 00:30:58.800
in secret, and in pieces.

00:30:58.800 --> 00:31:02.390
She had been removing items
from the house one by one.

00:31:02.390 --> 00:31:04.500
A single dress from her closet.

00:31:04.500 --> 00:31:06.640
Then a lone photo from the album.

00:31:06.640 --> 00:31:08.800
A fork from the silverware drawer.

00:31:08.800 --> 00:31:10.810
A quilt from under the bed.

00:31:10.810 --> 00:31:14.010
Every week she took something new.

00:31:14.010 --> 00:31:15.310
A sweater.

00:31:15.310 --> 00:31:16.610
A pair of shoes.

00:31:16.610 --> 00:31:17.970
A Christmas ornament.

00:31:17.970 --> 00:31:22.390
A book. Slowly her presence
in the house grew thinner.

00:31:22.390 --> 00:31:25.000
She'd been at it almost a year
when Samuel and his father began

00:31:25.000 --> 00:31:28.430
to sense something, a sort
of instability, a puzzling

00:31:28.430 --> 00:31:32.660
and disturbing, and sometimes even
sinister feeling of depletion.

00:31:32.660 --> 00:31:34.100
It struck them at odd moments.

00:31:34.100 --> 00:31:35.580
They looked at the
bookshelf and thought,

00:31:35.580 --> 00:31:38.640 position:56%
'Don't we own more books than that?'

00:31:38.640 --> 00:31:39.940
They walked by the china cabinet

00:31:39.940 --> 00:31:43.520
and felt sure something
was missing, but what?

00:31:43.520 --> 00:31:45.370
They could not give it
a name, this impression

00:31:45.370 --> 00:31:48.410
that life's details
were being reorganized.

00:31:48.410 --> 00:31:50.810
They didn't understand that the
reason they were no longer eating

00:31:50.810 --> 00:31:53.160
Crock-Pot meals was that
the Crock-Pot was no longer

00:31:53.160 --> 00:31:54.720
in the house.

00:31:54.720 --> 00:31:56.090
If the bookshelf seemed bare,

00:31:56.090 --> 00:31:59.000
it was because she had
pruned it of its poetry.

00:31:59.000 --> 00:32:02.240 position:56%
If the china cabinet seemed a little
vacant, it was because two plates,

00:32:02.240 --> 00:32:06.010
two bowls, and a teapot had
been lifted from the collection.

00:32:06.010 --> 00:32:10.700
They were being burglarized
at a very slow pace.

00:32:10.700 --> 00:32:12.590
'Didn't there used to be
more photos on that wall?'

00:32:12.590 --> 00:32:15.850
Samuel's father said, standing at
the foot of the stairs, squinting.

00:32:15.850 --> 00:32:19.230
'Didn't we have that picture
from the Grand Canyon up there?'

00:32:19.230 --> 00:32:20.620
'No,' Samuel's mother said.

00:32:20.620 --> 00:32:21.980
'We put that picture away.'

00:32:21.980 --> 00:32:25.080
'We did? I don't remember that.'

00:32:25.080 --> 00:32:27.700
'It was your decision.'

00:32:27.700 --> 00:32:30.640
'It was?' he said, befuddled.

00:32:30.640 --> 00:32:33.690
He thought he was losing his mind.

00:32:33.690 --> 00:32:36.800
Years later in a high school
biology class Samuel heard a story

00:32:36.800 --> 00:32:40.130
about a certain kind of African
turtle that swam across the ocean

00:32:40.130 --> 00:32:41.970
to lay its eggs in South America.

00:32:41.970 --> 00:32:45.380
Scientists could find no
reason for the enormous trip.

00:32:45.380 --> 00:32:47.270
Why did the turtles do it?

00:32:47.270 --> 00:32:49.990
The leading theory was that
they began doing it eons ago

00:32:49.990 --> 00:32:53.720
when South America and Africa
were still locked together.

00:32:53.720 --> 00:32:56.120
Back then only a river might
have separated the continents,

00:32:56.120 --> 00:32:58.540
and the turtles lay their
eggs on the river's far bank.

00:32:58.540 --> 00:33:00.820
But then the continents
began drifting apart,

00:33:00.820 --> 00:33:04.000
and the river widened by
about an inch per year

00:33:04.000 --> 00:33:06.980
which would have been
invisible to the turtles.

00:33:06.980 --> 00:33:10.190
So they kept going to the same
spot, the far bank of the river,

00:33:10.190 --> 00:33:13.210
each generation swimming a tiny
bit farther than the last one.

00:33:13.210 --> 00:33:16.550
And after 100 million years of
this the river had become an ocean,

00:33:16.550 --> 00:33:19.960
and yet the turtles never noticed.

00:33:19.960 --> 00:33:24.050
This, Samuel decided, was the
manner of his mother's departure.

00:33:24.050 --> 00:33:25.950
This was how she moved away.

00:33:25.950 --> 00:33:27.250
Imperceptibly.

00:33:27.250 --> 00:33:29.320
Slowly. Bit by bit.

00:33:29.320 --> 00:33:31.600
She whittled down her life
until the only thing left

00:33:31.600 --> 00:33:34.120
to remove was herself.

00:33:34.120 --> 00:33:39.200 position:56%
On the day she disappeared, she left
the house with a single suitcase."

